    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The coefficients of thermal expansion for concrete and steel are remarkably close, typically ranging from 10 to 12 x 10^-6 /°C for both materials. This similarity is crucial because it means they expand and contract at nearly the same rate when temperatures change, preventing the development of excessive internal stresses that could cause cracking or debonding.\n\nHowever, if the expansion rates were significantly different, the differential movement could lead to failure. For instance, if the steel expanded much faster than the concrete, the steel would try to pull away from the concrete, potentially breaking the bond or causing the rebar to slip. Conversely, if the concrete expanded faster, it could exert outward pressure on the steel, leading to crushing or spalling of the concrete cover.\n\nTo mitigate these risks, engineers often use expansion joints in large structures and ensure proper concrete cover to protect the steel from corrosion, which can alter the material properties over time. Additionally, the rough surface of the rebar helps maintain the bond even under slight differential movements.\n\nIn summary, the close match in thermal expansion coefficients ensures that the composite action remains effective throughout the structure's lifecycle, allowing the concrete and steel to work together seamlessly under varying environmental conditions.",
